 \begin{abstract}
-Data streams that must be monitored for structural change are now
-routine --- patient vital signs in intensive care, correlated sensor
-channels in industrial systems, panels of asset returns --- and every
-false alarm carries a concrete operational cost.  Such streams are
-serially dependent, increasingly high-dimensional, and rarely admit a
-credible parametric model.  Standard cumulative sum (CUSUM) change-point
-procedures assume independent or parametrically specified input, and their
-false-alarm guarantees break down precisely in this regime, where the
-serial dependence is unknown and the observation dimension is large.
-Reviving the classical innovations principle with a learned
-recurrent predictor, this paper removes the predictable part of the
-dependence and applies CUSUM to what remains, and it supplies the
-probabilistic theory such a scheme has so far lacked.
-For contractive recurrent neural networks (RNNs) we prove that the hidden
-state admits a Doob decomposition into a predictable component and a
-martingale-difference innovation, that this innovation stabilizes
-geometrically toward its stationary counterpart, and that the accumulated
-innovations obey a functional central limit theorem.
-%
-For the resulting detector --- the Innovation CUSUM, which applies a Page
-CUSUM to learned prediction innovations --- we establish a \emph{complete,
-distribution-free} sequential-monitoring guarantee: an exponential lower
-bound on the in-control average run length and a matching upper bound on the
-out-of-control detection delay, together yielding the classical
-exponential-false-alarm / logarithmic-delay trade-off, all requiring only
-$L^2$-accuracy of the predictor and \emph{no} parametric model for the data.
-%
-A further result explains why the predictor should be \emph{learned}: under
-nonlinearity in the conditional mean, any fixed linear residualization
-carries an irreducible innovation defect, whereas a consistent learned
-predictor drives it to zero --- so the learned innovations are the closest
-to the martingale-difference ideal, and the detector calibrates without
-knowing the model form.
-%
-Empirical studies on synthetic and real data --- including the Nile
