-
+Sequential monitoring is difficult when observations are serially
+dependent, high-dimensional, and not described by a trusted parametric
+model.  This paper revisits the classical innovations principle in a
+learned-prediction setting: a recurrent predictor removes the
+serially predictable component of the stream, and a CUSUM statistic is
+applied to the resulting prediction innovations.  The theoretical
+development is deliberately two-tier.  First, for operator-norm
+contractive recurrent neural networks, the hidden state admits a Doob
+decomposition into a predictable component and a martingale-difference
+innovation; the transient innovation approaches its stationary
+counterpart geometrically, and its partial sums satisfy a functional
+central limit theorem.  A bridge result then shows how this hidden-state
+stabilization translates into small conditional drift for prediction
+residuals when the recurrent readout approximates the Bayes predictor.
+Second, for any fitted predictor whose residuals have bounded conditional
+mean drift and conditional sub-Gaussian tails, the resulting Innovation
+CUSUM has an exponential lower bound on the in-control average run length
+and a logarithmic upper bound on the post-change detection delay.  The
+guarantee is model-free with respect to the data-generating dynamics, but
+not assumption-free: it depends on explicit residual-drift, tail, and
+post-change signal conditions.  We also identify when learning is
+statistically useful.  If the conditional mean is nonlinear, fixed linear
+residualization has an irreducible innovation defect, while a consistent
+learned predictor can remove it.  Simulations and two real-data examples
+illustrate the theory: learned innovations are competitive under correct
+linear specification and improve calibration under nonlinear
+misspecification, short calibration windows, and multivariate monitoring.
 \end{abstract}
 
